# Cursor Rules Location

## 🚨 CRITICAL: EDIT EXISTING RULES FIRST
**Before creating new cursor rule files:**
1. Search existing rule files in `.cursor/rules/` to see if any can be extended
2. Check if existing rules can be modified to include new functionality
3. Only create new rule files when no existing rule can serve the purpose

### REQUIRED: Move rule files, do not recreate

When reorganizing rule files:

- Use `git mv` to move and rename rule files under `.cursor/rules/`
- Do not copy content into a new file and delete the old one; preserve history
- Update any internal references (like `@rule-name.mdc`) in the index and docs

Example:

```bash
git mv .cursor/rules/old-name.mdc .cursor/rules/new-descriptive-name.mdc
sed -i '' 's/@old-name.mdc/@new-descriptive-name.mdc/g' .cursor/rules/index.mdc
```

How to add new cursor rules to the project

1. Always place rule files in PROJECT_ROOT/.cursor/rules/:
    ```
    .cursor/rules/
    ├── your-rule-name.mdc
    ├── another-rule.mdc
    └── ...
    ```

2. Follow the naming convention:
    - Use kebab-case for filenames
    - Always use .mdc extension
    - Make names descriptive of the rule's purpose

3. Directory structure:
    ```
    PROJECT_ROOT/
    ├── .cursor/
    │   └── rules/
    │       ├── your-rule-name.mdc
    │       └── ...
    └── ...
    ```

4. Never place rule files:
    - In the project root
    - In subdirectories outside .cursor/rules
    - In any other location

5. Cursor rules have the following structure:

````
---
description: Short description of the rule's purpose
globs: optional/path/pattern/**/* 
alwaysApply: false
---
# Rule Title

Main content explaining the rule with markdown formatting.

1. Step-by-step instructions
2. Code examples
3. Guidelines

Example:
```typescript
// Good example
function goodExample() {
  // Implementation following guidelines
}

// Bad example
function badExample() {
  // Implementation not following guidelines
}
```
````
